    "content": "Yes, this works.\n\n\"Traditional metaphysics\" is what the reader expects to see and immediately understands. The TN does the precise work of specifying \"traditional relative to what\" without burdening the main text. And the pairing with \"post-metaphysics\" reads naturally -- \"traditional metaphysics\" and \"post-metaphysics\" are already a recognizable pair in English philosophical prose (Habermas uses exactly this pairing).\n\nOne small note: the TN should make clear that 前 is the author's coinage, not a standard term -- something like: \"前形而上学 (literally 'pre-metaphysics'): the author's term for the metaphysical tradition prior to the nihilistic crisis. Rendered here as 'traditional metaphysics,' following the author's own gloss.\" This prevents the reader from thinking \"traditional metaphysics\" is the author's original phrasing rather than a translation choice."
